AU  - Romer, David
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 20
IS  - 1
SP  - 105
EP  - 122
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/07/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(87)90060-2
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393287900602
AB  - The paper analyzes the effects of financial shocks on an economy in which individuals hold money to make purchases and in which the frequency of conversions of other assets into money is endogenous. The paper thus extends the work of Sanford Grossman and Laurence Weiss (1983) and Julio Rotemberg (1984) by allowing agents to choose the timing of trips to the bank. There are two major conclusions. First, the economy's response to a nominal interest rate shock exhibits large cycles. Second, the economy's response differs dramatically, both qualitatively and quantitatively, from its response when the timing of trips is fixed.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Comovements in aggregate and relative prices: Some evidence on neutrality
AU  - Pauls, B.Dianne
JO  - Journal of Monetary Economics
VL  - 20
IS  - 1
SP  - 155
EP  - 168
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/07/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(87)90063-8
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393287900638
AB  - This paper develops an alternative test of the neutrality of anticipated monetary policy. A multi-good equilibrium model along the lines of Barro and Hercowitz is used to derive a neutrality proposition for anticipated movements in the aggregate price level and to demonstrate its equivalence econometrically to the exogeneity of relative prices with respect to the aggregate price level. Multivariate causality tests provide a basis for testing these restrictions. The empirical results provide mixed evidence for the equilibrium models, while the variation in the findings across industries suggests a role for supply-side disturbances in explaining comovements in aggregate and relative prices.
ER  - 

