SP  - 141
EP  - 153
PY  - 1987
DA  - 1987/07/01/
SN  - 0304-3932
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1016/0304-3932(87)90062-6
UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304393287900626
AB  - This paper examines whether the sales mechanism used by the FDIC in failed bank auctions results in wealth transfers from the FDIC to the acquiring banks. We test this hypothesis by examining the returns to winning bidders in FDIC auctions. We find positive abnormal returns to these bidders. More importantly, we find a negative and significant relation between the returns to winning bidders and the number of bidders participating in the auction. This evidence suggests that the FDIC's auction procedures do generate wealth transfers.
